266. The metaphor implied in the colloquial use of tondere for ‘to cheat’ seems to be here referred to the helpless state of a man in the hands of a barber. Elsewhere the victim’s loss of his money is compared to a sheep's loss of its fleeee, so that tondere would correspond oxactly to our term ‘to fleece.7 Thus in the Bacchides, where the white-haired old men are playfully likened ‘co a couple of strayed sheep (vv. 1121 sqq.), the cunning slave announees his scheme to the audience in these words (v. 241):

Adibo hunc, quem quiden] ego hodie faciam hic arietem Phrixi, itaque tondebo auro usque ad uiuam cutem.
